00:00:14,179 --> 00:00:19,879
So there's a dangerous belief hovering around
the people who follow self-improvement.

2
00:00:19,879 --> 00:00:22,899
it's the belief that If you work hard enough,
you're going to succeed.

3
00:00:22,899 --> 00:00:27,799
Now before you misconceive anything, bring
up that shot-gun and shoot me in the head.

4
00:00:27,800 --> 00:00:29,140
let me explain.

5
00:00:29,140 --> 00:00:34,000
Self development gurus frequently emphasize
the idea that you should never give up. And

6
00:00:34,000 --> 00:00:35,119
I couldn't agree more.

7
00:00:35,119 --> 00:00:39,780
But, I also believe that it's equally important
to learn when to quit.

8
00:00:39,780 --> 00:00:44,530
Many great people have wasted their lives
in fruitless endeavors. With the ingrained

9
00:00:44,530 --> 00:00:48,859
idea that If you hustle strong enough. Things
will turn out well.

10
00:00:48,859 --> 00:00:51,130
Big, big misconception.

11
00:00:51,130 --> 00:00:54,070
If you're into any kind of project or creative
work.

12
00:00:54,070 --> 00:00:59,700
It's essential for you to learn when precisely
you should keep up and when to give up, stop

13
00:00:59,700 --> 00:01:02,710
wasting your time and move on to something
else.

14
00:01:02,710 --> 00:01:05,989
Seth Godin laid down a clear blueprint for
this.

15
00:01:05,989 --> 00:01:09,809
He said that when people venture onto a business
or project.

16
00:01:09,810 --> 00:01:15,019
there has to be three different types of plateaus
that a person is more likely to encounter.

17
00:01:15,019 --> 00:01:17,280
The first one is called "The Dip"

18
00:01:17,280 --> 00:01:21,390
when you start off.
in the beginning you're noticing gradual growth.

19
00:01:21,390 --> 00:01:22,950
but then the dip happens.

20
00:01:22,950 --> 00:01:26,880
The dip is the long slog between starting
and mastery.

21
00:01:26,879 --> 00:01:31,099
The dip isn't that discouraging actually,
it helps you move faster to your goal as long

22
00:01:31,099 --> 00:01:33,449
as you are willing to hustle to break through
it.

23
00:01:33,450 --> 00:01:35,900
The first time I picked the guitar it was
fun.

24
00:01:35,900 --> 00:01:37,159
but a few months later.

25
00:01:37,159 --> 00:01:42,340
I found out that in order to become a master,
you have to learn a thousand scales, chords

26
00:01:42,340 --> 00:01:44,728
and another thousand combination of techniques.

27
00:01:44,728 --> 00:01:47,810
I realized at the time, that I hit a dip.

28
00:01:47,810 --> 00:01:53,700
The dip is that period where you work, and
work, and work without perceiving any tangible

29
00:01:53,700 --> 00:01:54,790
results.

30
00:01:54,790 --> 00:01:59,368
It's the hardest part about learning anything
and only those who persevere will get to the

31
00:01:59,368 --> 00:02:00,759
other side of the dip.

32
00:02:00,759 --> 00:02:06,438
The second type of plateau is called the "cul-de-sac"
(wich is the french word for "dead end")

33
00:02:06,438 --> 00:02:10,068
let's say you've encountered a dip and decided
to persevere.

34
00:02:10,068 --> 00:02:13,848
Afterwards, there are two possible outcomes
that are liable to occur.

35
00:02:13,848 --> 00:02:18,530
The first one is that after persevering through
the dip, your growth curve peaks up. You're

36
00:02:18,530 --> 00:02:20,408
success rate gets higher.

37
00:02:20,408 --> 00:02:23,209
But there's a second possibility wich is the
cul-de-sac.

38
00:02:23,209 --> 00:02:28,729
A cul-de-sac is when You're working and hustling
for months, even years but nothing seems to

39
00:02:28,729 --> 00:02:29,268
pan out.

40
00:02:29,269 --> 00:02:35,019
A cul-de-sac is a dead end, if you see one
while working on any kind of project you better

41
00:02:35,019 --> 00:02:37,150
quit as soon as possible.

42
00:02:37,150 --> 00:02:41,269
I know this is harsh advice but
It's worthless to invest your whole life in

43
00:02:41,269 --> 00:02:45,139
something that's not going to pay off sooner
or later.

44
00:02:45,139 --> 00:02:50,459
So the dip is good, it's a path toward mastery.
If you're on a dip, keep pushing.

45
00:02:50,459 --> 00:02:55,789
You recognize a dip when you start to see
tangible results after a few months.

46
00:02:55,789 --> 00:03:01,548
But the cul-de-sac is a dead end. a dead end
is when you're working for years without achieving

47
00:03:01,549 --> 00:03:03,739
any considerable results.

48
00:03:03,739 --> 00:03:08,099
It's better to stop and start something else
that will grant you the potential to reach

49
00:03:08,098 --> 00:03:13,138
a dip, rather than to keep punching at a wall
that's never going to break.

50
